# Why and how should we study women's mental health?

[**Thursday session lecture:** Dr Gemma Sharp: Introduction to Women's Mental Health](https://www.dropbox.com/s/5dtwtoibl9atlzi/repro_mental_health_2022_psy3430.pptx?dl=0){style="color:#9F45CD"}

[**Required Reading:** Kuehner C (2016) Why is depression more common among women than among men](https://www.dropbox.com/s/q9bd3h5nfv69cl7/Kuehner-lancetpsych.pdf?dl=0){style="color:#cd5b45"}

[**Required Reading:** Howard, Ehrilch, Gamlen & Oram (2017) Gender-neutral mental health research is sex and gender biased. The Lancet Psychiatry](https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lanpsy/article/PIIS2215-0366(16)30209-7/fulltext){style="color:#cd5b45"}

[**Optional Reading:** Department for Health and Social Care (2022) Introduction: Why Do We Need a Women's Health Strategy?, Women's Health Strategy](https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/womens-health-strategy-for-england/womens-health-strategy-for-england#introduction){style="color:#45B7CD"}

[**Optional Reading:** Nogrady (2021) The chemical question: does focusing on hormones undermine mental healthcare? The Guardian](https://www.theguardian.com/society/2021/may/09/the-chemical-question-does-focusing-on-hormones-undermine-mental-healthcare){style="color:#45B7CD"}

### Guided discussion questions:

-   Why is women's mental health an important topic?
-   Why should women's mental health research and care take a biopsychosocial approach?
-   Why should women's mental health research and care take a lifecourse approach?
-   Could shining a light specifically on women's mental health undermine gender equality?

